{"id":"2108.07674","submitter":"Nikolaos Tetradis","authors":"Nikolaos Tetradis (Athens U.)","title":"De Sitter entropy as holographic entanglement entropy","comments":"7 pages, 2 figures, Contribution to the Proceedings of the 4th\n  International Conference on Holography, String Theory and Discrete Approach,\n  Hanoi, Vietnam, 2020","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We review the results of refs. [1,2], in which the entanglement entropy in\nspaces with horizons, such as Rindler or de Sitter space, is computed using\nholography. This is achieved through an appropriate slicing of anti-de Sitter\nspace and the implementation of a UV cutoff. When the entangling surface\ncoincides with the horizon of the boundary metric, the entanglement entropy can\nbe identified with the standard gravitational entropy of the space. For this to\nhold, the effective Newton's constant must be defined appropriately by\nabsorbing the UV cutoff. Conversely, the UV cutoff can be expressed in terms of\nthe effective Planck mass and the number of degrees of freedom of the dual\ntheory. For de Sitter space, the entropy is equal to the Wald entropy for an\neffective action that includes the higher-curvature terms associated with the\nconformal anomaly. The entanglement entropy takes the expected form of the de\nSitter entropy, including logarithmic corrections.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 17 Aug 2021 15:15:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-18"}
